<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/AE58F21F-3622-4382-97BB-1359BD183E9F"><gtr:id>AE58F21F-3622-4382-97BB-1359BD183E9F</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Glasgow</gtr:name><gtr:department>College of Arts</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Avenue</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Glasgow</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>G12 8QQ</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Scotland</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/AE58F21F-3622-4382-97BB-1359BD183E9F"><gtr:id>AE58F21F-3622-4382-97BB-1359BD183E9F</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Glasgow</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Avenue</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Glasgow</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>G12 8QQ</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Scotland</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/22F39122-C185-467E-AEDA-E5B60A150093"><gtr:id>22F39122-C185-467E-AEDA-E5B60A150093</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Sean</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Francois</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Johnston</gtr:surname><gtr:orcidId>0000-0001-6156-9768</gtr:orcidId><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE018483%2F1"><gtr:id>21C77F42-FA4F-4770-89D7-695CEEC201D6</gtr:id><gtr:title>The nuclear engineer: shaping a profession</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E018483/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The nuclear engineer emerged as a new kind of technical specialist in the late 1940s in response to government initiatives around the world to develop atomic energy.&amp;nbsp;The identity of these specialists ? forming an unusually closed, state-allied discipline ? was shaped in the context of post-war politics and energy programmes, and evolved along with popular perception of their subject over the following fifty years. &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>Nuclear engineers as a specialist community were also unusual in representing a social ?step-function?: the technology coalesced rapidly after the war and engendered professional aspirations from those diverted to work in the newly invented field.&amp;nbsp;This sudden event permits precise study of the social and cultural ramifications of interest for the sociology of the professions, history of technology and cultural history.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>A comparative analysis of different national experiences in Britain, America and Canada will help elucidate the distinct political and economic factors operative in those contexts.&amp;nbsp;The differing accounts of this new field generated by its practitioners, sponsors, historians and curatorial interpreters are also of considerable historiographical interest.&amp;nbsp;This project will study the birth, consolidation and subsequent mutation of nuclear engineers in the first three countries where they practiced with the aim of better understanding how new disciplines and professions become established.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-08-14</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-08-15</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>78048</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>disseminated to historians of technology and science.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2010</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>BF7D1C97-65B2-4AA1-89E1-454E4A07D017</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Cultural,Societal</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>56531a9c1dd368.14050568</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections,Other</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The research evaluated and provided insights on:

? the implications of inadequate state management of the nuclear engineering profession, particularly concerning the historical provision of Further and Higher Education training and occupational recognition for the nuclear engineering professions;

? the negative consequences of security and restricted flow of nuclear knowledge for technical innovation, provision of safe technologies and public perceptions of its experts;

? the advantages of an active and independent voice for nuclear engineering specialists in neutral roles (eg as consumer ombudsmen or safety consultants in representative social organisations);

? the value of adopting a profile for the nuclear engineering profession more typical of their counterparts in cognate engineering disciplines, particularly in adopting explicit codes of ethical practice and in representing societal needs, rather than those of their industry;

? the evaluation of nuclear engineers as competent problem solvers, but too often identified narrowly with their industries, governments or short-term technical goals.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The research findings are relevant to the public and policy debate concerning the so-called 'nuclear renaissance', and in particular UK government support for a new generation of nuclear power stations, for initiatives to train a new generation of nuclear workers and for the future of national regulation of the engineering professions. The project focus on government management of specialist nuclear workers is directly relevant to the rebuilding of further- and higher-education programmes to train, support and oversee such experts. The research findings can inform government and institutional policymaking for further- and higher-education provision; management and support of technical experts; and, planning for emerging technologies.



For scholars of the professions, this research provides a details transnational study of three countries' experience of nuclear development. Its highlight on the roles of security, inter-professional relations and public identity can inform studies of currently emerging specialist groups.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>9333AD4E-596A-4FD2-847C-C4D0A79B6304</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>r-3811189917.6716714b2f01056</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Digital/Communication/Information Technologies (including Software),Education,Energy,Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>50509085-5B59-4A4D-9D89-1D73FBA40CD8</gtr:id><gtr:title>Defining the nuclear engineer in the UK, USA and Canada, 1940-65</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/a155dd9288eec6a36e54ad7be5580428"><gtr:id>a155dd9288eec6a36e54ad7be5580428</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Sean Johnston (author)</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>1900-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>r_4314589874cbd651ba</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>DEA76EE1-CD73-45C7-8027-1AB93CD26F1E</gtr:id><gtr:title>Narratives of ethnic identity among practitioners in community settings in the northeast of England</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Ethnic and Racial Studies</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/b239b96ee14e4763143e0851828c8ef5"><gtr:id>b239b96ee14e4763143e0851828c8ef5</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Parks J</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2014-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>588b6086022365.98259035</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>5DAF27BA-9AB2-4688-8A8B-FD5E8B877E34</gtr:id><gtr:title>Making the I